Born in Trenton, NJ in 1985, Eric was raised in central NJ until attending Drexel University in Philadelphia for his undergraduate degree in English. He received his MFA in Creative Writing from Rutgers University-Camden in 2010. While living in Philadelphia, Eric became involved with soundtrack work for various live-scare haunted attractions and small film and theater productions. His work has been featured in Terror Behind the Walls at Eastern State Penitentiary, the Wisconsin Fear Grounds, the Philadelphia Fringe Festival, and in films by Reel 9 Productions.  In 2011, he co-wrote and directed an original musical, "Meat Man," with writer/director Erin Davis, for which he composed the original music featured in the production.

In 1952, he volunteered to direct _"Bandstand" (1952)_ (qv), a new show on Philadelphia's WFIL-TV, featuring local teens dancing to the latest hits, debuted with 'Bob Horn (I)' (qv) as host and took off after 'Dick Clark (I)' (qv), already a radio veteran at age 26, took over in 1956. Became a national institution that made Clark a star. Broadcast live in its early years, even after it became part of the ABC network's weekday afternoon lineup in 1957 as "American Bandstand." Yates pulled records, directed the cameras, queued the commercials and communicated with Clark. This extraordinary director managed to grab every exciting moment, pictures influenced a whole generation of young people across America. Directed American Bandstand for 17 years.

Renee Zawawi or should we say WOW-Y is Hollywood's new "IT" girl. Zawawi has taken LA by surprise and is relentless in her pursuit of success. Zawawi was born in Philadelphia, USA, but grew up overseas. She is descendant from Arabian blood, which makes her the first Arabian Princess to become a Hollywood actress, musician and producer. Renee is trilingual and speaks Arabic, French and English. Her voice is breathy, unique, with a bubbly effusiveness. She has a sophisticated personality and a chic sense of fashion. She is classic with a contemporary edge. She is humorous, intelligent, and creative. Best known for Legends and Happy Hour.

Shirley Yamaguchi was born to Japanese parents in Manchuria in 1920. She used the Chinese name Li Xianglan (Ri Koran in Japanese) and made pro-Japanese films in Japanese-occupied areas in China. She also was a popular singer and some of her hits, including "fragrance of the night" (Ye Lai Xiang), remain popular even today. After the Japanese surrendered she escaped treason and possible execution by revealing her Japanese heritage.
